        id: 'ev1-client-intake',
        type: 'client-intake',
        title: 'Investigation Report — CrediCatch Practices',
        date: 'September 15, 2027',
        content: '<div class="doc-section"><div class="doc-section-title">Investigation Summary</div><p><strong>Subject:</strong> CrediCatch Financial (App-based micro-lending)<br><strong>Trigger:</strong> 1,200% year-over-year increase in personal bankruptcy filings listing CrediCatch as a primary creditor.</p></div><div class="doc-section"><div class="doc-section-title">Background</div><p>CrediCatch requires users to link their primary bank accounts via Open Banking APIs to access "financial health tracking." We received reports that users receive aggressive push notifications for instant loans exactly when their accounts drop below \u20AC15, or immediately after a direct debit fails. Many users, feeling they have no other choice to keep their electricity on or avoid eviction, accept these loans despite exorbitant interest rates.</p></div><div class="doc-section"><div class="doc-section-title">Victim Impact Profile: Lukas N.</div><p>A representative victim, Lukas N., lost his job in June. The app detected his lack of salary deposit and his subsequent late rent payment. Within an hour of his rent payment failing, the app offered him a \u20AC500 loan. He accepted. Over three months, the AI repeatedly offered "rollover" loans timed precisely to his dwindling balance, resulting in a debt spiral now exceeding \u20AC4,000. He is currently facing eviction.</p></div>'
