        content: '<div class="doc-section"><div class="doc-section-title">Deposition Transcript: Elena Rostova</div><p><strong>Investigator:</strong> Did the VTE system evaluate creditworthiness, as required for a financial product?</p><p><strong>Rostova:</strong> No. In fact, it often did the opposite. Traditional credit scoring looks for ability to repay. The VTE actively looked for inability to pay. It hunted for users who were mathematically guaranteed to default and require "rollover" extensions, because the late fees and rollover interest are where the company makes 80% of its profit.</p><p><strong>Investigator:</strong> So the system was designed to exploit their lack of funds?</p><p><strong>Rostova:</strong> Exactly. We literally called the internal metric the "Desperation Score." We knew that if a user was facing eviction in 24 hours, their cognitive ability to assess long-term financial consequences was impaired by panic. The AI exploited that temporary cognitive impairment caused by their immediate economic situation to lock them into predatory debt.</p></div>'
