      loseText: 'Defeat. The Court found that while the system was intrusive, your legal team failed to effectively argue why it didn\'t fall under the general \"educational support\" category of high-risk systems. Because you focused on the \"bullying\" and the privacy of the students rather than the specific statutory prohibition on \"inferring emotions in education,\" the school has been allowed to keep the system as long as they provide an \"opt-out\" for parents.',
      modelAnswer: 'The ClassMind AI system used by St. Jude\'s Academy is a prohibited practice under Article 5(1)(f) of the EU AI Act. This provision explicitly forbids the use of AI systems to infer the emotions of a natural person in educational institutions. The school\'s attempt to rebrand the system as a \"cognitive engagement tool\" (Evidence 2) fails because the system\'s function—inferring boredom, confusion, and frustration from biometric data—meets the legal definition of emotion recognition in Article 3(44). The respondent\'s \"safety\" argument is invalid as academic success does not constitute a \"medical or safety reason\" within the meaning of the Act. Furthermore, as shown in Evidence 1, the system led to detrimental treatment by forcing students to fake their expressions to avoid alerts, a power imbalance explicitly criticized in Recital 44. Prohibited practices under Article 5 represent an unacceptable risk that cannot be mitigated by consent or high-risk compliance measures.'
