            {
              id: 'arg3-weak',
              quality: 'weak',
              text: 'Your Honour, the statistics show that this system is a failure. It is wrong 85% of the time! That isn\'t \"proactive policing,\" it\'s just guessing. If a human officer made that many mistakes, they would be fired. The police are using \"science\" as a mask for bias. My client is one of the 85% of innocent people being harassed. This kind of data-driven approach is just a way to make discrimination look official, and the court should ban it because it doesn\'t actually work to catch real criminals.',
              judge_response: 'I agree the statistics are concerning, but you must explain why \"guessing based on characteristics\" is a violation of the specific Article 5(1)(d) legal test.',
              legal_reasoning: 'Correct in spirit but lacks statutory precision. It focuses on the "failure" of the system rather than the legal definition of the prohibited practice.'
            },
            {
              id: 'arg3-wrong',
              quality: 'wrong',
              text: 'Your Honour, the statistics are irrelevant because the AI Act only applies to \"fully automated\" systems. Since the police manual says that officers use the data to \"prioritize\" their work, the system is semi-automated and falls outside the scope of the Regulation. Furthermore, the AI Act only protects \"consumers,\" and since people in a police database are not buying anything, they do not have any rights under this law. The NRPF can continue to use the statistics to improve their internal operations without any interference from this court.',
              judge_response: 'Counsel, that is a double error. The AI Act applies to all AI systems, not just fully automated ones, and it absolutely protects individuals from law enforcement abuses. It is not a \"consumer protection\" law.',
              legal_reasoning: 'Fundamental error. It invents a "fully automated" requirement and a "consumer only" scope, both of which are completely false under the AI Act.'
            }
