    verdict: {
      winText: 'Victory! The Court has issued a permanent injunction against the use of Crim-Pulse. Justice Vossen ruled that the system is a prohibited practice under Article 5(1)(d), stating that \"predicting criminality based on a person\'s postal code and family history is the antithesis of justice in a digital age.\" The court found that the NRPF\'s \"human-in-the-loop\" was a procedural sham and that the system assessed risk based solely on prohibited profiling characteristics. The police have been ordered to delete all recidivism scores and cease all pre-emptive stops based on the algorithm.',
      loseText: 'Defeat. The Court found that while the system was intrusive, your legal team failed to effectively argue why the socioeconomic data did not count as \"verifiable facts.\" Because you focused on the \"unfairness\" of the profiling rather than the specific requirement that facts must be \"directly linked to a criminal activity,\" the court has allowed the NRPF to continue using the system as a \"non-binding advisory tool.\"',
      modelAnswer: 'The NRPF\'s Crim-Pulse system is a prohibited practice under Article 5(1)(d) of the EU AI Act. This provision forbids AI systems that make individual risk assessments to predict the likelihood of a person committing a criminal offence solely based on profiling or personality characteristics. The respondent\'s attempt to use the \"support\" exception fails because that exception requires the human assessment to be based on \"objective and verifiable facts directly linked to a criminal activity\" (i.e., evidence of a specific crime). As shown in Evidence 2 and 4, Crim-Pulse uses general profiling markers (postal code, family history, psychometrics) for individuals with no prior record. The \"human-in-the-loop\" (Evidence 3 and 5) was a formalistic bypass that did not involve any independent factual assessment of criminal involvement. Consequently, the system represents an unacceptable risk and must be decommissioned.'
    }
