        title: 'RE: Article 5(1)(g) Concerns',
        date: 'July 10, 2025',
        content: '<div class="doc-section"><div class="doc-section-title">Email Thread: Regulatory Strategy</div><p><strong>From:</strong> CEO, Aura Analytics<br><strong>To:</strong> Legal Lead (M. Dubois)<br><strong>Date:</strong> July 9, 2025 18:22</p><p>Marcus, investors are spooked by the new EU AI Act provisions. If they classify Prism-AI as a prohibited biometric system under Article 5, we lose the entire European retail market. I need a bulletproof legal workaround immediately. How do we bypass the ban on inferring sensitive traits?</p><hr><p><strong>From:</strong> Legal Lead (M. Dubois)<br><strong>To:</strong> CEO, Aura Analytics<br><strong>Date:</strong> July 10, 2025 09:14</p><p>The text is indeed strict. The EU AI Act explicitly prohibits biometric categorisation for the purpose of inferring race, religion, or politics. <div class="doc-highlight">Our best defense is to argue we are not \'individually\' categorizing natural persons</div> because our software actively deletes the raw images and never links the face to a legal identity, credit card, or name. We should aggressively lobby to claim that \'anonymous commercial categorization\' for advertising purposes is merely a high-risk transparency issue under Annex III, not an absolute prohibited practice. Do not use the word "individual" in any future press releases.</p></div>'
