      modelAnswer: 'The University violated the EU AI Act on three primary counts. First, the training data for the high-risk proctoring system (Annex III, 3b) failed the Article 10(3) representativeness test; a 95% Caucasian dataset is statistically inappropriate for a diverse population and leads to biased outcomes (Evidence 4). Second, the University failed its human oversight obligations under Article 14. By implementing an \"automatic failure\" policy (Evidence 3) and allowing a rubber-stamp review process (Evidence 5), they failed to minimize automation bias or enable the human to effectively disregard the AI output. Finally, the University breached Article 9 by failing to implement technical mitigations for a known risk to neurodivergent students identified before deployment (Evidence 6). High-risk systems must be safe and non-discriminatory for their entire intended population; aggregate efficiency does not excuse systemic bias.'
