  verdict: {
    winText: 'Victory! The Equality Tribunal has issued a permanent injunction against the use of HireSmart AI at CloudScale Tech. Justice Vossen ruled that the system violated Article 10(3) of the AI Act, finding that a training dataset derived from historical male-dominated hires is not \"sufficiently representative\" for a modern recruitment tool. Crucially, the court found that the provider knowingly failed its risk management duties under Article 9 by refusing to mitigate a known risk of gender discrimination in favor of \"predictive accuracy.\" CloudScale has been ordered to manually re-evaluate all female candidates rejected by the AI.',
    loseText: 'Defeat. The Court found that while the gender disparity was \"concerning,\" your legal team failed to effectively prove that the use of historical data was a violation of the AI Act rather than a valid business practice. Because you focused on the \"unfairness\" to the applicants rather than the specific statutory requirements for bias examination in Article 10(2)(f), the court has allowed the company to continue using the system as long as they provide a generic \"Diversity Statement\" on their website.',
    modelAnswer: 'CloudScale Tech violated the EU AI Act on two primary grounds. First, HireSmart AI failed the Article 10 data governance mandate. Under Art. 10(2)(f), providers must specifically examine training data for possible biases that have a negative impact on fundamental rights. CloudScale was aware that the 88% male historical dataset (Evidence 2) was creating biased weights against female-specific keywords (Evidence 3 & 4) but failed to perform the mandatory detoxification or balancing required by Art. 10(3). Second, the provider breached Article 9 (Risk Management). Art. 9(2) requires that risks be reduced through design and development. By identifying a known risk of gender discrimination but explicitly choosing \"No Mitigation\" (Evidence 6), the provider ignored the mandatory risk management hierarchy. High-risk systems in employment must be safe and non-discriminatory for the entire labor pool; historical efficiency cannot justify the automation of gender bias.'
  }
