            text: 'Your Honour, the company is protected by the \"Right to Information\" under the Digital Services Act (DSA). The DSA states that companies only have to inform people about AI if it is used to moderate \"illegal content.\" Since promotion scoring is not illegal content, the company was under no obligation to disclose anything. The AI Act is a subordinate law that must be interpreted in light of the DSA\'s pro-business transparency rules, which allow companies to keep their internal algorithms secret to prevent competitors from stealing their leadership metrics.',
            judge_response: 'Counsel, you are citing the wrong law entirely. The DSA applies to online platforms, not internal workplace AI. And the AI Act is not \"subordinate\" to the DSA in this context. Your argument is legally incoherent.',
