      type: 'internal-email',
      title: 'RE: Feedback on District 9 Rejections',
      date: 'April 2025',
      content: '<div class="doc-section"><div class="doc-section-title">Email Thread: Compliance Risk Assessment</div><p><strong>From:</strong> Chief Legal Counsel (M. Vargas)<br><strong>To:</strong> Head of Risk (Marcus Vane)<br><strong>Date:</strong> April 12, 2025 10:15</p><p>Marcus, I am reviewing the Q1 rejection metrics. The legal team is extremely worried that the 68% rejection rate in immigrant-heavy zones (specifically District 9 and Sector 4) looks exactly like algorithmic redlining. We are highly exposed under the AI Act\'s bias rules. Can we drop the postal code variable?</p><hr><p><strong>From:</strong> Head of Risk (Marcus Vane)<br><strong>To:</strong> Chief Legal Counsel (M. Vargas); Data Science Team<br><strong>Date:</strong> April 12, 2025 11:30</p><p>Maria, if we pull the postal code data, our predictive accuracy for the entire portfolio drops by 8 points. That translates to millions in potential default losses. <div class="doc-highlight">We decided to keep the geospatial weights.</div> We can justify it to the regulators as \'economic neighborhood stability\' and \'property value forecasting\' rather than ethnicity or national origin. The algorithm is blind to race, so we are legally covered.</p></div>'
