      type: 'policy-document',
      title: 'Judicial Manual: AI Risk Use',
      date: 'June 2025',
      content: '<div class="doc-section"><div class="doc-section-title">Northern Territory Judicial Manual: AI Integration</div><p><strong>Section 3:</strong> Application of Pre-Trial Risk Assessments</p></div><div class="doc-section"><div class="doc-section-title">3.1 Weight of Algorithmic Recommendations</div><p>The introduction of BailBound AI is intended to harmonize bail decisions across all districts, eliminating the subjective leniency or harshness of individual magistrates.</p><p>While the algorithmic score is technically advisory, judges are strongly encouraged to treat scores above 75 (High/Critical) as <div class="doc-highlight">verifiable, objective indicators of community risk and flight probability.</div> To maintain statewide consistency and protect public safety, any judicial decision that deviates significantly downward from the BailBound recommendation (e.g., granting Release on Recognizance to a High-Risk defendant) must be exhaustively justified in writing in the official sentencing remarks. Such deviations will be subject to automatic administrative review by the Chief Magistrate\'s office.</p></div>'
