            text: 'Your Honour, the Ministry has violated Article 22 of the GDPR regarding the right not to be subject to a decision based solely on automated processing. Since the judge followed the AI exactly, the decision was effectively automated. Under GDPR, Thomas Miller had a right to a human explanation of the AI\'s logic. Because the Ministry failed to provide a plain-language summary of how the ten-year sentence was calculated, they have violated the data protection rights of the defendant and the sentence must be overturned and all court records deleted immediately.',
            judge_response: 'Counsel, while GDPR is relevant, we are litigating under the AI Act. And since a human judge *did* sign the order, the "solely automated" threshold of Article 22 is difficult to reach. Does the AI Act not provide a more specific remedy for high-risk systems?',
            legal_reasoning: 'Fundamental error. It applies the wrong framework (GDPR) and focuses on the \"solely automated\" test, which is easily bypassed by a human signature. The AI Act\'s Art 14 oversight requirements are much more stringent for high-risk systems.'
