            text: 'Your Honour, the Ministry is exempt from Article 14 under the \"Sovereign Immunity\" clause of the Digital Services Act. That clause states that any AI used for the core functions of the state, such as justice or defense, is not subject to the transparency or oversight rules of secondary regulations. Since the Ministry is a public body performing a public duty, the AI Act does not apply to the internal workings of the court system. The defendant has no standing to challenge the administrative tools used by the judiciary to ensure sentencing consistency.',
            judge_response: 'Counsel, there is no \"Sovereign Immunity\" clause in the DSA, and the AI Act explicitly lists the judiciary as a high-risk user in Annex III. Public bodies are the *primary* targets of these rules. Your argument is legally baseless.',
            legal_reasoning: 'Fundamental error. It invents a non-existent exemption and wrongly claims the AI Act doesn\'t apply to the state, which directly contradicts the Regulation\'s scope and Annex III.'
