      date: 'September 12, 2025',
      content: '<div class="doc-section"><div class="doc-section-title">Applicant Profile & Credentials</div><p><strong>Name:</strong> Amira El-Sayed<br><strong>Profession:</strong> Senior Architect<br><strong>Nationality:</strong> [Redacted - Tier 3 Country]</p><p>I applied for a standard short-stay Schengen visa to attend a professional architecture conference in Berlin. I provided a flawless application: my bank statements showing a consistent balance of €85,000, a permanent employment contract, a paid return flight, and proof of my previous, fully compliant five-year Schengen visa which expired last year.</p></div><div class="doc-section"><div class="doc-section-title">Rejection & Informal Feedback</div><p>Despite this, my application was rejected within 24 hours. The official notice was completely generic, citing an "unquantifiable risk of overstay." I appealed in person at the consulate. <div class="doc-highlight">The reviewing officer told me off-the-record that the software gave me an automatic \'Red Flag\' the exact moment my passport country was entered into the system.</div> It didn\'t matter that I am wealthy, employed, and have never overstayed a visa a day in my life. The AI system literally cannot see past my passport. I am being judged entirely by my geographic origin, not my individual actions or merits.</p></div>'
