    winText: 'Victory! The Court has issued a permanent injunction against the use of nationality as a primary scoring factor in FrontierGuard AI. Justice Morel found that the NMA violated Article 10(3) by using non-representative and biased training data. Crucially, the court ruled that the agency\'s deliberate choice to prioritize "predictive accuracy" over the mandatory duty to mitigate known biases was a willful breach of its risk management duties under Article 9. The NMA has been ordered to manually re-evaluate Amira\'s application and all other Tier 3 rejections from the last six months.',
    loseText: 'Defeat. The Court found that while the nationality weighting was "aggressive," the NMA\'s mandate for border security gave them broad discretion under the AI Act. Because you failed to effectively link the bias in the dataset to the specific statutory failure in the risk management hierarchy, the court ruled that the statistical correlation with overstays was a valid "objective fact," shielding the agency from liability.',
    modelAnswer: 'The NMA violated the EU AI Act on two primary counts. First, FrontierGuard AI failed the Article 10 data governance mandate. Under Art. 10(2)(f), providers must examine training data for possible biases that negatively impact fundamental rights. The agency was aware that the 45% nationality weight (Evidence 2) served as a discriminatory proxy (Evidence 4) but failed to perform the mandatory detoxification or balancing required by Art. 10(3). Second, the provider breached Article 9 (Risk Management). Art. 9(2) requires that risks be reduced through design and development. By identifying the bias risk (Evidence 3) but choosing "No Mitigation" (Evidence 6) to protect accuracy, the provider ignored the mandatory risk management hierarchy. High-risk systems in migration must be safe and non-discriminatory; border security objectives do not justify the automated violation of the principle of individual assessment.'
