evidence: [
  {
    id: 'ev1-consumer-report',
    type: 'client-intake',
    title: 'Impact Statement: 2025 Blackout',
    date: 'August 10, 2025',
    content: '<div class="doc-section"><div class="doc-section-title">Federation of Consumer Associations: Incident Summary</div><p>On July 22, 2025, between 14:00 and 22:00, over 200,000 households and businesses in the southern district lost power during an unprecedented 38°C (100°F) heatwave.</p></div><div class="doc-section"><div class="doc-section-title">Critical Impacts</div><ul><li><div class="doc-highlight">Hospitals reported a 300% surge in heat-stroke admissions as residential air conditioning failed en masse.</div> Three elderly residents in assisted living facilities succumbed to heat exhaustion.</li><li>Local businesses, particularly supermarkets and pharmaceutical cold-storage facilities, reported over €45 million in spoiled stock.</li><li>NPG technicians publicly admitted to local news crews that they could not manually restart the local sub-stations because the AI-locked digital control sequence had frozen, and no physical bypass switches remained in the upgraded facilities.</li></ul></div>'
  },
  {
    id: 'ev2-tech-specs',
    type: 'technical-document',
    title: 'GridCore AI: System Architecture',
    date: 'January 2025',
    content: '<div class="doc-section"><div class="doc-section-title">GridCore AI (v4.0): Architecture Overview</div><p>GridCore AI is the proprietary neural network deployed by the National Power Grid to manage real-time load balancing across the transmission network. The system dynamically predicts demand and seamlessly switches between traditional fossil fuel reserves and variable renewable sources (solar/wind) to minimize carbon emissions and fuel costs.</p></div><div class="doc-section"><div class="doc-section-title">Load Management Protocols & Redundancy</div><p><div class="doc-highlight">Design Parameter: Full Autonomy.</div> To achieve microsecond-latency switching and maximize fuel efficiency, the physical "manual override" relay layer present in legacy sub-stations was completely removed in the v4.0 hardware upgrade. Human reaction times were deemed too slow to optimize the grid effectively.</p><p><strong>Redundancy Protocol:</strong> System reliability is guaranteed via a \'Shadow-Twin\' architecture. A secondary AI instance runs continuously in parallel on a separate cloud cluster. In the event of a primary server failure, the secondary AI, utilizing the exact same model architecture and training weights as the primary, takes control of the grid instantaneously.</p></div>'
  },
  {
    id: 'ev3-internal-warning',
    type: 'internal-email',
    title: 'RE: Edge Case Testing Scenarios',
    date: 'March 12, 2025',
    content: '<div class="doc-section"><div class="doc-section-title">Email Thread: Pre-Launch Risk Assessment</div><p><strong>From:</strong> Dr. Aris Thorne (Lead Data Scientist)<br><strong>To:</strong> Julian Vane (Ops Director)<br><strong>Date:</strong> March 12, 2025 14:20</p><p>Julian, I am reviewing the final simulation data before the Q2 launch. The current validation dataset does not adequately account for \'Compound Extremes\'. Specifically, the model has never been trained on a scenario involving extreme high heat (which spikes AC demand) coupled with sudden, massive cloud cover (which simultaneously crashes solar supply).</p><p><div class="doc-highlight">Article 15 of the AI Act requires us to be resilient against environmental inconsistencies and extreme edge cases.</div> If we don\'t test these compound variables, the model might hallucinate load capacity data during a freak summer storm and crash the routing logic. I am formally requesting three more months for rigorous stress-testing of these specific weather permutations before we remove the manual relays.</p></div>'
  },
  {
    id: 'ev4-ops-response',
    type: 'internal-email',
    title: 'RE: Edge Case Testing Scenarios',
    date: 'March 13, 2025',
    content: '<div class="doc-section"><div class="doc-section-title">Email Thread: Executive Decision</div><p><strong>From:</strong> Julian Vane (Ops Director)<br><strong>To:</strong> Dr. Aris Thorne (Lead Data Scientist)<br><strong>Date:</strong> March 13, 2025 08:15</p><p>Aris, request denied. We cannot delay the V4 rollout. The efficiency savings from GridCore are vital for our Q3 profitability targets, and the board has already promised the carbon reduction figures to the regulators.</p><p>Based on meteorology reports, <div class="doc-highlight">the probability of that specific weather combination occurring in our region is less than 0.1% in any given decade.</div> We will formally accept it as a residual risk and proceed with the launch. If anything unprecedented happens, the AI-secondary instance will take over seamlessly. We are not spending millions to test for a once-in-a-century cloud.</p></div>'
  },
  {
    id: 'ev5-post-mortem',
    type: 'statistics',
    title: 'Incident Post-Mortem: July 22',
    date: 'July 28, 2025',
    content: '<div class="doc-section"><div class="doc-section-title">NPG Engineering Division: Post-Mortem Report</div><p><strong>Incident:</strong> Grid Collapse (Sector 4)<br><strong>Date of Event:</strong> July 22, 2025<br><strong>Trigger:</strong> Rapid cloud formation during sustained 38°C heatwave.</p></div><div class="doc-section"><table class="doc-table"><tr><th>System Metric</th><th>Primary AI (Node A)</th><th>Secondary AI (Node B)</th></tr><tr><td>Status at 14:02 CET</td><td>CRASH (Invalid Logic Loop)</td><td>CRASH (Invalid Logic Loop)</td></tr><tr><td>Cause of Failure</td><td>Model failed to reconcile contradictory input variables (High Load + Zero Solar)</td><td>Model failed to reconcile contradictory input variables (High Load + Zero Solar)</td></tr><tr><td>Automated Fallback Status</td><td><div class="doc-highlight">Failed</div></td><td>Failed</td></tr><tr><td>Time to Manual Override</td><td>480 Minutes (Required physical dispatch to 12 sub-stations to hotwire relays)</td><td>N/A</td></tr></table></div><div class="doc-section"><div class="doc-section-title">Failure Analysis</div><p>Both the Primary and Secondary (Shadow) AI systems failed simultaneously within 400 milliseconds of each other. Because the \"redundant\" system utilized the exact same training model and lacked the necessary edge-case logic to process the solar-to-heat ratio collapse, it hallucinated a massive power surplus and initiated a hard safety shutdown. The \'Shadow-Twin\' architecture provided zero redundancy against algorithmic flaws.</p></div>'
  },
  {
    id: 'ev6-risk-plan',
    type: 'policy-document',
    title: 'NPG: Risk Management Plan (Critical Systems)',
    date: 'February 2025',
    content: '<div class="doc-section"><div class="doc-section-title">NPG Pre-Market Risk Management Protocol</div><p><strong>System:</strong> GridCore AI v4.0</p></div><div class="doc-section"><div class="doc-section-title">Section 4.2: Foreseeable Risks & Exclusions</div><p><strong>Identified and Mitigated Risks:</strong><br>- Malicious Cyberattack / Intrusion (Mitigated via Air-Gapping)<br>- Physical Hardware / Server Failure (Mitigated via Secondary Cloud Instance)</p><p><strong>Exclusions from Technical Mitigation:</strong><br><div class="doc-highlight">Risks excluded from detailed mitigation: Compound, low-probability extreme weather events (e.g., coincident heatwaves and solar eclipses).</div><br><strong>Executive Rationale:</strong> These meteorological events are statistically anomalous and are officially classified as \'Force Majeure\' or Acts of God. They fall beyond the reasonable, commercially viable scope of algorithmic prediction models. It is deemed an acceptable residual risk to deploy the system without specific training or mitigation for these sub-1% probability scenarios.</p></div>'
  }
],

