      content: '<div class="doc-section"><div class="doc-section-title">Confidential Legal Memo: Regulatory Exposure</div><p><strong>Prepared by:</strong> External Counsel (Digital Rights Group)</p></div><div class="doc-section"><div class="doc-section-title">Art. 50(1) Interactive Disclosure Review</div><p><strong>Compliance Risk Level:</strong> Severe / High Exposure.</p><p><div class="doc-highlight">Article 50(1) creates a mandatory duty to inform natural persons they are interacting with an AI system.</div> This rule applies universally to any system intended to directly interact with humans.</p><p>Crucially, there is no statutory exception for "therapeutic benefit," "user comfort," or the "illusion of empathy." Unless the system is strictly utilized by an authorized state agency for law enforcement purposes (criminal investigations), the disclosure is a hard, unavoidable requirement at the point of first interaction. Burying the disclosure in a generic Terms of Service document does not satisfy the "designed and developed to inform" standard of the Regulation.</p></div>'
