    winText: 'Victory! The AI Office has ruled that Aether AI violated the AI Act. Justice Vossen found that the provider breached Article 53(1) by failing to provide the mandatory technical documentation required by Annex XI and failing to inform downstream providers of critical medical-domain limitations as required by Annex XII. The court rejected the absolute \"Trade Secret\" defense, ruling that commercial interests cannot override the mandatory transparency safeguards needed for high-risk medical applications. Aether AI has been ordered to pay a significant fine and issue an updated, detailed summary of its training content.',
    loseText: 'Defeat. The Court found that while the documentation was \"minimal,\" the respondent\'s right to protect its intellectual property created sufficient legal ambiguity. Because you failed to effectively prove that the omitted compute and energy data were \"strictly necessary\" for the AI Office\'s safety assessment, the court has allowed Aether AI to continue operating as long as they provide a generic \"Medical Disclaimer\" on their API portal.',
    modelAnswer: 'Aether AI violated the EU AI Act on three primary counts as a GPAI provider. First, it failed Article 53(1)(a) by omitting mandatory elements of technical documentation for authorities, specifically compute resources and energy consumption (Annex XI, 2d & 2e). Second, it breached Article 53(1)(b) by failing to provide downstream integrators like MediTech with a \"good understanding\" of the model\'s limitations; the suppression of known 44% medical accuracy benchmarks (Evidence 5 & 6) violated the Annex XII requirement for a description of known limitations. Third, the firm breached Article 53(1)(d) by failing to provide a \"sufficiently detailed\" training summary. The respondent\'s \"Trade Secret\" defense fails because the Act mandates these disclosures to ensure the safety of the AI value chain. The AI Office template is a mandatory requirement, and commercial secrecy does not grant an exemption from the fundamental duty to enable the safe use of high-risk systems built upon foundational models.'
