        oppositionArgument: 'Dr. Reinhardt continues: "Even if the Authority finds Art. 22 applies, the Art. 22(2)(a) exception is plainly satisfied. Mr. Mueller applied for a home loan \u2014 a contract. The decision as to whether to enter that contract is necessarily made by the credit institution. Automated credit scoring is expressly necessary for the performance of pre-contractual steps taken at the data subject\'s request under Art. 22(2)(a). This is the paradigm case for the contract exception. And my client has satisfied Art. 22(3) by ensuring a credit officer confirms every decision \u2014 that officer is available for Mr. Mueller to contact. The safeguard is in place."',
        writePrompt: 'Review the CreditMind interface specification (ev2) and the former officer\'s statement (ev5). Using Art. 22(3) GDPR, explain why the credit officer confirmation step does not satisfy the mandatory human intervention safeguard even if the Art. 22(2)(a) exception applies.',
        minWords: 20,
        options: [
          {
            id: 'arg2-strong',
            quality: 'strong',
            text: 'Honourable Authority, Art. 22(3) requires \u201Cat least the right to obtain human intervention on the part of the controller, to express his or her point of view and to contest the decision.\u201D This demands a human capable of genuinely reviewing the specific decision. The CreditMind interface shows officers only a score and two buttons \u2014 no input weightings, no reasoning, no documentation. An officer who cannot see why a score was generated cannot intervene in any meaningful sense. Former officer Bauer confirms she had no tools to interrogate or override the model. Mr. Mueller\'s right to contest the decision requires a human with access to the logic driving it.',
            judge_response: 'Counsel, that is a well-grounded analysis of Art. 22(3)\'s requirements. The Authority notes that human intervention that is structurally incapable of examining the underlying reasoning cannot satisfy the contestation right the provision mandates. The interface specification and Ms. Bauer\'s testimony are material evidence on this point.',
            legal_reasoning: 'Correctly grounds the argument in the specific text of Art. 22(3) and identifies why the interface design defeats the safeguard: you cannot contest a decision whose reasoning you cannot access. Links the technical architecture to the legal requirement, proving the safeguard is structurally rather than merely operationally absent.'
          },
          {
            id: 'arg2-plausible',
            quality: 'plausible',
            text: 'Honourable Authority, even accepting Art. 22(2)(a) applies, EuroCredit cannot invoke the contract exception because no contract existed between Mr. Mueller and EuroCredit at the time of the decision. Art. 22(2)(a) permits automated decisions where necessary for the \u201Cperformance of a contract\u201D between the data subject and the controller. Mr. Mueller applied for a loan and was rejected before any contract was formed. The exception requires a pre-existing or concluded contractual relationship \u2014 not a decision about whether to enter one at all. Since EuroCredit used automation to decide whether to contract with Mr. Mueller, Art. 22(2)(a) is unavailable regardless of what safeguards were in place. The prohibition in Art. 22(1) applies in full.',
            judge_response: 'Counsel, the scope of Art. 22(2)(a) is contested on these facts and you raise a legitimate point about pre-contractual steps. However, Art. 22(2)(a) explicitly covers \u201Csteps prior to entering into a contract\u201D at the data subject\'s request. The stronger argument on this round is directed at Art. 22(3)\'s safeguard requirements, which the opposition specifically invoked. Please address whether the officer confirmation satisfies Art. 22(3).',
            legal_reasoning: 'The pre-existing contract argument misreads Art. 22(2)(a), which expressly covers pre-contractual steps \u2014 making this a factual legal error, not just a misdirection. The argument also fails to engage with Art. 22(3)\'s specific safeguard requirements, which is what the opposition argued and what this round requires the student to rebut.'
          },
          {
            id: 'arg2-weak',
            quality: 'weak',
            text: 'Honourable Authority, the credit officer review is clearly not working. A person who cannot even see the reasons for a decision cannot help the applicant challenge it. Mr. Mueller had no way of knowing that his postcode was the problem, and even if he had called the helpline, no officer would have been able to explain the algorithm to him or change the outcome. The whole point of having a human review is so that the applicant can get a fair hearing from someone who can actually do something about the result. EuroCredit\'s process gives applicants no real opportunity to challenge decisions that affect their lives.',
            judge_response: 'Counsel, you identify a genuine practical problem but have not anchored your argument in the specific requirements of Art. 22(3). The Authority needs you to identify the legal standard and explain how EuroCredit fails to meet it, not just describe the practical inadequacy of the process.',
            legal_reasoning: 'Correctly identifies the practical failure of the review process but does not cite Art. 22(3) or explain its specific requirements. Does not engage with the \u201Cright to express point of view\u201D or \u201Ccontest the decision\u201D elements that the provision mandates and that the interface design defeats.'
          },
          {
            id: 'arg2-wrong',
            quality: 'wrong',
            text: 'Honourable Authority, Art. 22(4) is the operative provision here. Mr. Mueller\'s postcode-linked socioeconomic index constitutes data revealing ethnic or social origin within the meaning of Art. 9 GDPR \u2014 postcode is a known proxy for demographic and ethnic composition in German housing markets. Processing such special category data in an automated credit decision requires explicit consent or substantial public interest under Art. 22(4). EuroCredit obtained neither. The use of postcode weighting in an automated system therefore violates Art. 22(4), which provides the most serious level of protection for automated decisions involving sensitive data. This is the primary infringement the Authority should address.',
            judge_response: 'Counsel, Art. 22(4) raises a potentially interesting question about proxy data and special categories, but postcode as a socioeconomic index is not straightforwardly \u201Cdata concerning ethnic or social origin\u201D within Art. 9 without substantial further argument. More importantly, the question before the Authority on this round is whether Art. 22(3)\'s safeguards are met. Please address that question directly.',
            legal_reasoning: 'Art. 22(4) and the proxy discrimination argument is legally ambitious but speculative without clear authority that postcode constitutes Art. 9 data. Critically, it fails to address Art. 22(3) at all, which is the provision the opposition invoked and the argument the round requires. Choosing the most serious possible provision without engaging the specific question posed is a fundamental advocacy error.'
          }
        ]
