    verdict: {
      winText: 'The Autoriteit Persoonsgegevens finds in favour of Mr. Garcia on all grounds. UrbanNest violated Art. 22(1) GDPR: TenantTrust\'s automatic rejection pathway, applied to Tomas\'s individual application without any human reviewer ever accessing his file, constitutes a solely automated decision that significantly affects his access to housing. UrbanNest violated Art. 13(2)(f): no disclosure of automated processing, complaint history weighting, or automatic rejection thresholds was made at the point of application. UrbanNest violated Art. 14(2)(g): complaint history data sourced from a third-party landlord database was processed without equivalent disclosure to Tomas. UrbanNest violated Art. 22(3) and Art. 15(1)(h): the rejection letter and access response provided no meaningful information about the complaint weighting logic. The Authority orders a fresh human-reviewed assessment of Tomas\'s application, prohibition on use of the complaint history feature pending independent bias audit, and referral for fine assessment under Art. 83(4) noting deliberate dismissal of the ethics reviewer\'s audit request.',
      loseText: 'The Authority dismisses Mr. Garcia\'s complaint. Without precise engagement with Art. 22(1)\'s individual-level assessment requirement, the Art. 13/14 disclosure obligations, or the Art. 22(3) and Art. 15(1)(h) safeguard and access requirements, the complaint fails to establish the violations alleged. UrbanNest\'s characterisation of threshold-setting as embedded human judgment, its generic privacy policy as adequate disclosure, and its helpline as an Art. 22(3) safeguard all survive unchallenged. Tomas\'s clean eight-year tenancy record, the biased training data, the dismissed ethics audit request, and the systemic rejection rate for complaint-history applicants all go unused. A tenant rejected for exercising his legal right to habitable conditions receives no remedy.',
      modelAnswer: 'UrbanNest violated Art. 22(1), Art. 13(2)(f), Art. 14(2)(g), Art. 22(3), and Art. 15(1)(h) GDPR. On Art. 22(1): the solely automated threshold is met. TenantTrust automatically rejected Tomas\'s application without his file reaching any human reviewer \u2014 Hoekstra confirms she never saw automatically rejected applications and had no access to those files. The human review queue applied only to borderline cases; Tomas was not in it. Setting a threshold is a policy decision; applying that threshold to Tomas\'s individual circumstances is what Art. 22(1) regulates. Housing rejection significantly affects access to accommodation, bringing it squarely within Art. 22(1)\'s scope. On Arts. 13(2)(f) and 14(2)(g): UrbanNest was required to disclose at application that automated decision-making including complaint history weighting would be used \u2014 Art. 13(2)(f) for data collected from Tomas directly, and Art. 14(2)(g) for the complaint history data sourced from a third-party landlord database. The controller cannot deflect these obligations onto TenantTrust as vendor: UrbanNest deployed the system and bears the disclosure obligation for the processing it chose to use. No specific logic was disclosed at any stage. On Art. 22(3) and Art. 15(1)(h): the right to express a point of view requires an opportunity to address the specific factor driving rejection \u2014 Tomas could not contest a complaint weighting he was never told about. The access response replicated the rejection letter rather than providing the meaningful logic information Art. 15(1)(h) mandates. The internal email shows UrbanNest knew the complaint feature was contested and chose to disclose nothing, engaging aggravated liability under Art. 83(4).'
    }
