      narrative: 'Andreas Petrov, a 58-year-old accountant, arrived at the emergency department of St. Maren Hospital at 19:14 on 6 November 2024 reporting severe dizziness, balance loss, and mild confusion. He presented without facial drooping or arm weakness \u2014 the classical stroke indicators. On arrival, a triage nurse entered his symptoms into TriageAI, the hospital\'s automated patient prioritisation system. The system assigned Andreas a Priority 4 score \u2014 \u201Cnon-urgent\u201D \u2014 based on his symptom profile not matching the standard acute stroke template in its training dataset. TriageAI\'s stroke recognition module had been trained predominantly on cases exhibiting classical anterior circulation strokes; posterior circulation strokes, which frequently present without facial or limb symptoms, were significantly underrepresented in the training data. Andreas waited three hours and eleven minutes before a physician assessed him. By then, he had sustained a posterior circulation stroke causing permanent damage to his vestibular and coordination systems. He will require lifelong physiotherapy and has been unable to return to work. At admission, Andreas signed a standard intake form containing the clause: \u201CI consent to computerised assessment of my clinical information to support hospital care decisions.\u201D The hospital maintains this clause constitutes explicit consent to TriageAI\'s automated prioritisation and that triage is in any event necessary for healthcare provision under Art. 9(2)(h) GDPR. Andreas brings a complaint before the German Federal Commissioner for Data Protection and Freedom of Information, the BfDI, arguing that his triage priority was determined by a solely automated system processing special category health data without adequate safeguards.',
      client: { name: 'Andreas Petrov', role: 'Patient, 58-year-old accountant; sustained permanent neurological damage from delayed treatment following algorithmic triage misclassification' },
      respondent: { name: 'St. Maren Hospital GmbH', type: 'Private hospital, data controller; processes health data under Art. 9' },
      setting: 'Bundesbeauftragte f\u00FCr den Datenschutz und die Informationsfreiheit (BfDI), Berlin \u2014 Formal Complaint Proceedings, Health Data and Automated Processing Chamber'
