              judge_response: 'Counsel, the AI Act framework will impose important obligations on high-risk healthcare AI systems, and the analysis you present may eventually be relevant in the appropriate forum. However, the AI Act does not grant Mr. Petrov an individual right before this Authority \u2014 GDPR Art. 22 does. You are before the BfDI on a data protection complaint. Please address Art. 22(1) directly.',
              legal_reasoning: 'The AI Act Annex III, point 5(a) argument is the plausible trap: it correctly identifies TriageAI as a high-risk system but is the wrong instrument before a DPA on a GDPR complaint. The AI Act creates system-level obligations on deployers and does not confer individual rights exercisable before a supervisory authority in GDPR proceedings. Art. 22 GDPR is the operative provision.'
