    verdict: {
      winText: 'The Autoriteit Persoonsgegevens finds in favour of DataWatch on all grounds. ShopSphere violated Art. 22(1) GDPR: PriceMind AI generates solely automated profiling-based decisions that similarly significantly affect consumers\' economic interests \u2014 premiums of up to 31.2% for identical products constitute financial impact within the EDPB\'s significant effects framework. ShopSphere violated Art. 13(2)(f): the privacy notice discloses recommendations personalisation but contains no mention of pricing, providing no meaningful information about the logic or consequences of the pricing processing. Art. 22(3) safeguards are absent: consumers who do not know personalised pricing exists cannot exercise any right to contest it, and no opt-out mechanism exists. The internal email documents deliberate concealment of a known compliance gap, engaging aggravated liability under Art. 83(4). The Authority orders immediate suspension of undisclosed personalised pricing, implementation of Art. 22(3)-compliant disclosure and opt-out mechanisms, and referral for substantial fine assessment noting the knowing disregard of the product manager\'s compliance flag.',
      loseText: 'The Authority dismisses DataWatch\'s complaint. Without precise engagement with Art. 22(1)\'s similarly significant financial effects test, the EDPB guidelines on profiling and financial impact, Art. 13(2)(f)\'s purpose-specific disclosure requirement, or Art. 22(3)\'s prerequisite information conditions, the complaint fails. ShopSphere\'s \u201Cnot compelled to buy\u201D defence, its generic personalisation disclosure, and its customer service channel as Art. 22(3) safeguard all survive unchallenged. The internal email\'s documentation of deliberate concealment, the data scientist\'s twice-raised compliance objections, the 31.2% price differential evidence, and the \u20AC14\u201331 million collective consumer harm estimate all go unused. Undisclosed profiling-based pricing continues across five EU Member States.',
      modelAnswer: 'ShopSphere violated Art. 22(1), Art. 13(2)(f), and Art. 22(3) GDPR. On Art. 22(1): PriceMind AI generates solely automated profiling-based pricing decisions that similarly significantly affect consumers within the meaning of Art. 22(1). The EDPB guidelines on profiling confirm that significant financial impact on economic interests qualifies as a similarly significant effect even without legal compulsion. Premiums of up to 31.2% \u2014 \u20AC68.90 more for a travel accessory \u2014 invisibly imposed based on automated device and postcode profiling constitute significant financial impact. The voluntary nature of purchase does not negate the financial significance: a consumer who unknowingly pays 28% above another user\'s price for the same product is significantly affected in their economic interests by the automated profiling decision. The pricing decision is solely automated: PriceMind generates an individualised price per session with no human review of individual pricing decisions. On Art. 13(2)(f): meaningful information about the logic and consequences of the pricing processing was required at the time of data collection. The privacy notice discloses recommendations personalisation and never mentions pricing. The word \u201Cprice\u201D does not appear in any automated processing disclosure. A recommendations consent does not cover a pricing purpose \u2014 these are materially different applications with materially different consequences. The internal email proves this gap was known and deliberately left unaddressed over the objections of two technical staff members. On Art. 22(3): the right to contest a decision requires prior knowledge of the decision\'s existence. Consumers who do not know personalised pricing is applied cannot exercise any Art. 22(3) right. No opt-out mechanism exists. Customer service is available only to consumers who have already independently discovered the violation. The deliberate dismissal of the product manager\'s compliance flag without obtaining a legal opinion, documented in internal correspondence, engages aggravated liability under Art. 83(4).'
    }
