            judge_response: 'Counsel, the AI Act transparency requirements for high-risk systems raise genuine concerns and may generate separate proceedings before the appropriate AI supervisory authority. However, Art. 13 AI Act imposes transparency obligations on providers and deployers, not a direct individual right of explanation enforceable by data subjects before a DPA. GDPR Art. 15(1)(h) provides James with a specific individual right enforceable before this Authority. Please engage Art. 15(1)(h) and Recital 63 directly.',
            legal_reasoning: 'The AI Act transparency argument is the plausible trap. Art. 13 AI Act imposes system-level transparency obligations on providers and deployers, not a direct individual right of explanation. It is enforced by AI market surveillance authorities, not DPAs in their primary capacity. GDPR Art. 15(1)(h) is the specific individual right directly enforceable before the CNIL. Using the AI Act as the primary framework before a DPA misidentifies both the instrument and the enforcement forum.'
