            text: 'Your Honour, LifeStream\'s Art. 34 assessment also violated Art. 14 DSA by failing to enforce its own Community Guidelines against self-harm content. Art. 14 requires all hosting services — not just VLOPs — to include and enforce terms prohibiting illegal content and content contrary to the platform\'s stated policies. LifeStream\'s Community Guidelines prohibit content that promotes self-harm. The algorithm serving 412 self-harm posts to a minor account constitutes a systemic failure to enforce those terms. The Art. 14 general obligation provides a lower evidentiary threshold than Art. 34/35 and should be the primary basis for the finding, supplemented by the Art. 34/35 VLOP violations.',
            judge_response: 'Counsel, Art. 14 is a general obligation for all hosting services. Art. 34 and 35 are the VLOP-specific obligations designed precisely for systemic algorithmic risks. Are you conceding the stronger VLOP-specific claim in favour of a weaker, lower-tier obligation?',
            legal_reasoning: 'The wrong-DSA-tier trap stated in the case brief. Art. 14 is a general hosting service obligation — it is a lower-tier provision that applies to all platforms and sets a less demanding standard. Pivoting to Art. 14 as the "primary basis" concedes the stronger Art. 34/35 VLOP-specific claim without legal justification. It is not wrong to mention Art. 14, but making it primary over Art. 34/35 is the structural error.'
