            id: 'arg1-wrong',
            quality: 'wrong',
            text: 'Your Honour, FeedFlow\'s recommendation algorithm should also be assessed under the EU AI Act Annex III, point 5, which covers AI systems used for profiling natural persons. A profiling AI system that operates without disclosure of its main parameters to affected users has not undergone the transparency and information obligations required under AI Act Art. 13 for high-risk AI systems. Art. 13 AI Act requires that providers of high-risk AI systems ensure those systems are transparent with respect to the information provided to deployers, including the purpose and intended use and the main characteristics of the system. The absence of parameter disclosure confirms the Art. 13 AI Act transparency obligation has not been met. I ask this body to find dual violations of DSA Art. 27 and AI Act Art. 13, and to refer the AI Act dimension to the relevant market surveillance authority.',
            judge_response: 'Counsel, AI Act Art. 13 governs transparency obligations for high-risk AI system providers toward deployers — not toward end users. Furthermore, AI Act compliance is supervised by market surveillance authorities, not DSCs. DSA Art. 27 is the specific user-facing transparency obligation for recommender systems and requires no supplementation from AI Act Art. 13.',
            legal_reasoning: 'An AI Act swap error misapplying Art. 13. AI Act Art. 13 governs transparency from high-risk AI system providers to deployers — not from platforms to end users. The user-facing transparency obligation for recommendation systems is specifically Art. 27 DSA. Introducing AI Act Art. 13 in DSA proceedings misunderstands both the direction of the obligation (provider-to-deployer vs. platform-to-user) and the enforcement architecture (market surveillance authorities, not DSCs).'
