          {
            id: 'arg2-plausible',
            quality: 'plausible',
            text: 'Your Honour, FeedFlow\'s refusal to offer a non-profiling alternative also violates GDPR Art. 21(2), which gives data subjects the right to object to processing of their personal data for direct marketing purposes at any time. While content recommendation is not technically direct marketing, the Court of Justice has interpreted "direct marketing" broadly in the digital context. Where a platform\'s recommendation algorithm drives commercial outcomes — including advertiser weighting, which the technical submission confirms represents 4% of ranking — users have an arguable right to object to that profiling under Art. 21(2). A non-profiling alternative would satisfy both Art. 27(3) DSA and the Art. 21(2) GDPR objection right simultaneously. I request the Coordinator note the GDPR dimension and refer it to the data protection authority alongside the Art. 27 finding.',
            judge_response: 'Counsel, GDPR Art. 21(2) applies specifically to direct marketing processing. Content recommendation, even with minor advertiser weighting, does not constitute direct marketing under GDPR. The GDPR referral introduces a legally weak parallel claim that does not advance the Art. 27(3) practicability analysis — the technical evidence already establishes that the chronological feed is practicable without needing GDPR supplementation.',
            legal_reasoning: 'A GDPR swap error applying Art. 21(2) direct marketing objection rights. GDPR Art. 21(2) is specifically for direct marketing — extending it to content recommendation by reference to minor advertiser weighting is a significant legal stretch that the judge correctly identifies as unlikely to succeed. Introducing a weak GDPR claim alongside a strong Art. 27(3) argument risks undermining the stronger claim by suggesting it needs supplementation and by creating an evidentiary distraction.'
          },
          {
            id: 'arg2-wrong',
            quality: 'wrong',
            text: 'Your Honour, the absence of a non-profiling alternative also triggers liability under the Consumer Rights Directive Art. 5, which requires traders to provide information about the main characteristics of a digital service before a consumer is bound by a contract. FeedFlow\'s recommendation algorithm is a main characteristic of its service — it drives 70% of video views. By not disclosing this characteristic or offering an alternative, FeedFlow has failed its pre-contractual information obligation. Consumers who did not know their feed was algorithmically curated could not have made an informed choice about entering the service contract. I request the Coordinator find a dual violation of DSA Art. 27(3) and CRD Art. 5, and refer the CRD dimension to national consumer authorities for contract law remedies.',
            judge_response: 'Counsel, CRD Art. 5 pre-contractual information requirements are enforced by national consumer protection authorities in national courts. DSA Art. 27(3) is the specific platform obligation for recommender system alternatives in these proceedings. The CRD referral introduces a contractual law framework with different remedies, different authorities, and a different legal standard that does not advance the Art. 27(3) finding before this Coordinator.',
            legal_reasoning: 'A consumer law swap error invoking CRD Art. 5 pre-contractual information obligations. The CRD governs pre-contractual disclosure in consumer contracts — it is enforced by national consumer authorities and national courts, not DSCs. Characterising the recommendation algorithm as a "main characteristic" under CRD Art. 5 is a legal stretch and introduces a framework requiring entirely separate proceedings. DSA Art. 27(3) is the specific, directly applicable standard.'
          }
