    narrative: 'AdStream is a news aggregation and social media VLOP with 55 million EU users. In March 2026, the consumer organisation TransparencyFirst EU filed a formal complaint with the Digital Services Coordinator documenting AdStream\'s advertising presentation practices during the six weeks preceding the May 2026 Czech parliamentary elections. TransparencyFirst EU\'s technical audit found that AdStream displayed three categories of content that its internal systems classified as paid advertising but that were not labelled as such in the user interface: (1) political advertising paid for by registered political parties and candidates, presented as regular news posts with no visible sponsor identification; (2) "sponsored content" articles from commercial advertisers, distinguished only by a marginally different background colour that user testing showed 73% of users could not identify as advertising; and (3) algorithmically promoted posts from advertisers using AdStream\'s "native boost" product, which inserts advertiser content into users\' organic feeds with no visible marker. For none of these three content types did AdStream display: a clear real-time label identifying the content as advertising; the identity of the sponsor (political party, company, or individual) who paid for the placement; or any information about the targeting parameters used to select the user as a recipient. AdStream defends itself by arguing that its sponsored content format is visually distinct from organic posts, that sophisticated users understand that some content is commercial, and that advertising identification requirements under EU law are satisfied by its privacy policy disclosures.',
