            quality: 'wrong',
            text: 'CloudCo\'s conduct violates Art. 102 TFEU as an unlawful tying arrangement. Tying is a well-established category of abuse of dominance under EU competition law. The Court of Justice in Hilti and Tetra Pak confirmed that a dominant undertaking that conditions access to a tying product on the purchase of a tied product commits an abuse, unless the bundling is objectively justified. CloudCo is dominant in cloud infrastructure — the Commission\'s designation confirms significant market power. The tying of CloudID and CloudPay to infrastructure forecloses the identity and payment processing markets to competitors without objective justification. The Commission should find an Art. 102 TFEU violation and impose a structural remedy separating CloudCo\'s infrastructure and ancillary services divisions.',
            judge_response: 'Counsel, this proceeding concerns Art. 5(8) DMA — a per se obligation applicable to designated gatekeepers without any requirement to prove market dominance, anticompetitive effects, or foreclosure. Art. 102 TFEU tying analysis is a different legal framework with different evidentiary requirements. The DMA exists precisely because Art. 102 proceedings are lengthy and require extensive market analysis. Please address Art. 5(8).',
            legal_reasoning: 'Competition law swap error — substitutes Art. 102 TFEU tying doctrine (requiring proof of dominance, tying and tied markets, foreclosure, no objective justification) for the DMA\'s per se rule. Even the remedy proposed — structural separation — is borrowed from competition law and has no direct basis in DMA enforcement.'
