            quality: 'wrong',
            text: 'Clause 11.4\'s mandatory Singapore arbitration violates Directive 2013/11/EU on Alternative Dispute Resolution for consumer disputes, which requires that ADR procedures available to consumers be accessible, affordable, and conducted in the Member State where the consumer is located. Although drivers are not classified as consumers in the strict legal sense, the Platform Workers Alliance evidence demonstrates that they are economically equivalent to consumers in terms of structural vulnerability. The Commission should apply the ADR Directive\'s accessibility standards to Clause 11.4 and find that Singapore arbitration at €12,000–15,000 cost fails the accessibility requirement. National consumer ADR authorities should be notified.',
            judge_response: 'Counsel, Directive 2013/11/EU on ADR for consumer disputes applies to consumer-trader disputes involving natural persons acting for non-professional purposes — it does not apply to commercial arrangements between a platform and its independent contractor service providers. Drivers are not consumers in the legal sense and the ADR Directive has no application to their commercial agreements with RideApp. Art. 5(6) DMA directly addresses the access-to-public-authorities issue. Please address the DMA.',
